name: Peter Neronha
tweet: 500 RI children are lead poisoned in their homes every year.  They deserve better.  So we're doing something about it.  Active. On offense.  That's the job.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: We fought for two years to get Rhode Island's now much-improved consumer protection law passed. And now we're using it again, this time to help Rhode Island car buyers. Active. On offense. That's the job.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: Important development. Now more likely this change of utility ownership will get full court review. By law regulators aren't the last word - courts are. Trying to ram a transaction through on regulator approval alone before judicial review can happen says a lot. None of it good.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: This opioid crisis isn't going away. And so we'll continue to fight on behalf of RI'ers.  Whether it's here, or healthcare, or public utilities or environmental and consumer protection, we are active, on offense, every day. That's the job.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: We pushed for changes in RI’s consumer protection law last year because we needed the tools to bring cases like this. An active AG’s office means protecting consumers, safeguarding our healthcare, ensuring environmental protection and fighting for lead-poisoned kids. More 2 come.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: Lot of healthcare news last week. Easy to miss this one but no less important. 500 RI kids are lead poisoned in their homes every year. This Court decision in our favor last week was a big step forward. Grateful to @RIHEALTH and @LeadSafeKidsRI for the partnership. More 2 come.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: 500 RI children are diagnosed with lead poisoning every year. 500. Remediating lead paint isn't difficult and it isn't expensive. If landlords won't do the right thing on their own, we'll keep taking them to court to make sure they do. Because children deserve better. Way better.

name: Peter Neronha
tweet: Grateful for this in-depth talk with @ConvergenceRI. This Office can and should have a major positive impact on the lives of all Rhode Islanders, if we think broadly about the scope of our authority and are prepared to take action - even unprecedented action - on their behalf.
